answers.answer:
One problem that I see all the time is companies and governments promising kinder farming (for example cage-free eggs or less crowding), but no one keeps a clear, trusted score of whether they really do it.

Animal-rights groups have to dig through thick reports, official letters, and their own farm investigations which is a very slow and costly process. In the meantime, leaders can brag about “progress” while cruel practices continue happening. I think it'd be incredibly helpful to have a public website that uses AI to:

- constantly read reports, contracts, and news in many languages;
- pull out the exact promises and any numbers showing progress;
- cross-check those claims with fresh satellite or drone photos and basic sensor data from farms;
- turn it all into simple scores that anyone from campaigners to investors can see.

Always-updated, automatic tracking would shine a light on broken promises and put real pressure on decision-makers to treat animals better.
